ANTHRAX - ARGENTINA (04): (BUENOS AIRES), BOVINE
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 31 Mar 2014
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


There has been a bovine anthrax outbreak in the district of Dolores, Buenos Aires Province. The outbreak was in a group of recently culled yearling calves which had been placed after separation on a pasture of natural grazing. The owners [unfortunately - Mod.MHJ] continue to believe that such animals are too young to be vaccinated and are refractory to infection with _Bacillus anthracis_ and had not had them vaccinated. In one week, 5 died. Their weights were in the 180-220 kg range.

The estancia is in the district of Dolores and had suffered an anthrax outbreak in April 2012; see 20120507.1125538. In that outbreak 82 cows died of anthrax essentially due to an initial misdiagnosis of enterotoxemia. The dams of these calves have been vaccinated with Sterne vaccine.

The Dolores district is an integral part of the rural anthrax surveillance area within the province and has seen 11 percent of the anthrax diagnoses made during the period 1977 to 2013.

--
Ramon Noseda
CEO/Laboratorio Azul Diagnostico SA
