[As usual, our thanks to Ramon.

As I have said before, nature is illiterate and pays no attention to beliefs and writing. She does what she does irrespective of them. With an undeniable pasture contamination associated with the 2012 severe outbreak, those calves were going to be exposed. The owner is very lucky that he got away with only 5 yearlings dying (to date).

The reason that some might believe that young stock are resistant to this disease is that anthrax is seen most commonly in adult stock and heifers awaiting their 1st breeding. It comes down to the vigor of grazing. Cows graze by wrapping their tongues around the grazing and yanking it out of the ground, thereby eating some 5-6 lbs of soil each day and by so doing putting themselves at risk. Also, they are bigger black-body attraction targets for biting flies. By definition suckling calves don't graze, though maybe are curious about it. Yearlings are grazing and so are at increasing risk as they grow.

Those who have visited an Argentine estancia in the Pampas have seen what marvelous natural grazing they have, thick and luxurious; I will admit to the temptation to pull out a salad bowl. But if the contamination is above average, those youngsters will be at risk.

For a map of Argentina showing the provinces, go to: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg. For Dolores, go to: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/AR/01/Dolores.html. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2370110,4.]
